is analysis of the school and its practices is a broader theoretical argument, which Abbott uses to redefine social objects as a sequence of interconnected events rather than as fixed entities. Abbott's theories grow directly out of the Chicago School's insistence that social life be located in time and place, a tradition that has been at the heart of the school since its founding one hundred years ago.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aChicago School of Sociology. 0aChicago school of sociologyxHistory. 0aSociologyzIllinoiszChicagoxHistory. 0aSociologyzUnited StatesvPeriodicalsxHistory. 0aSociologyzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aGaziano, Emanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package Archive 1960-1989z978311066784440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226222738423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226222738.jpg  a978-3-11-066784-4  UChP eBook-Package Archive 1960-1989c1960d1989  aGBV-deGruyter-alles